    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your loan interest is calculated based on your *remaining principal balance* at the beginning of each month. This means that in the early stages of your loan, a larger portion of your fixed monthly payment goes toward covering the accrued interest, leaving less for the principal. As your principal balance slowly decreases, the amount of interest calculated each month also shrinks, meaning more of your payment will start going toward reducing the actual loan amount over time.",
      "source": "target",
